Issues, risks and improvements

1. CORS set to “*”  
   What is wrong  
   • Any web site on the Internet can issue XMLHttp-Requests to your API.  
   • If later you enable cookies or Authorization headers (`credentials: true`) the
     wildcard will break the CORS spec and browsers will refuse the request.  
   • Opens the door for XSRF-style attacks, information leakage and easier abuse
     by bots.  

   How to fix  

```js
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = [
  'https://app.example.com',
  'https://admin.example.com'
];

app.use(cors({
  origin(origin, cb) {
    // allow server-to-server or tools without an Origin header
    if (!origin) return cb(null, true);

    if (ALLOWED_ORIGINS.includes(origin)) return cb(null, true);
    return cb(new Error('Origin not allowed by CORS'));
  },
  credentials: true,                  // only if you really need cookies / auth hdrs
  methods: 'GET,POST,PUT,DELETE',
  allowedHeaders: 'Content-Type,Authorization'
}));
```

   • Keep the list in an env variable or config file so that production,
     staging, local dev etc. can differ.  
   • Log or metric failed CORS checks to discover unexpected callers.

2. Huge JSON body limit (50 MB)  
   What is wrong  
   • A single 50 MB request can tie up the event loop for hundreds of
     milliseconds and allocate large buffers → DoS vector.  
   • Parsing very large JSON objects is CPU-intensive and can crash the
     process on small containers/functions.  
   • Most APIs only need a few KB of JSON; files should be uploaded through a
     streaming endpoint (e.g. multipart/form-data or S3 pre-signed URLs).  

   How to fix  

```js
// Put the limit in env so you can tune it without code changes
const JSON_LIMIT = process.env.JSON_LIMIT || '1mb';
app.use(express.json({ limit: JSON_LIMIT }));
```

   • If you really must accept large payloads, switch to a streaming
     parser (`express.raw`, `busboy`, `multer`, etc.) and process the chunks
     instead of buffering everything in memory.

3. No validation / sanitisation of incoming JSON  
   • Prototype-pollution attacks are still possible if you later merge objects
     without guarding against __proto__, constructor, prototype keys.  
   • Always validate the body with zod / joi / yup / class-validator etc.
     before using it.

4. Missing common security middleware  
   • Add `helmet()` to set secure headers.  
   • Enable rate-limiting (`express-rate-limit`) to further reduce DoS risk.  
   • Consider `hpp` (HTTP Parameter Pollution) middleware.

5. Error handling / logging not shown  
   • Wrap CORS origin callback or body-parser in a central error handler so that
     invalid requests return 400/413 instead of crashing the process.

6. Performance  
   • Place `cors` and `express.json` before any route so headers and body
     parsing happen once (looks OK in the snippet, just emphasize).  
   • Add `compression()` if you serve large JSON responses.

Take-away patch

```js
require('dotenv').config();
const express = require('express');
const cors    = require('cors');
const helmet  = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();

// --- Security middlewares ---
app.use(helmet());

const allowed = (process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS || '').split(',');
app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, cb) => {
    if (!origin || allowed.includes(origin)) return cb(null, true);
    return cb(new Error('Blocked by CORS'));
  },
  credentials: true
}));

app.use(express.json({ limit: process.env.JSON_LIMIT || '1mb' }));
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
// -------------------------------------

// … routes …

module.exports = app;
```

This configuration removes the open wildcard, limits body size to a sane
default, and layers on basic hardening to make the API safer and more
performant.
